content.description: This climb is also on the south side of King (to the right of the off-width/dihedral), but is much, much more difficult.  The descent is over the overhanging portion of King Rocks prominent southern prow, causing a definite risk to ones rope.  While being lowered, once past the overhang, one has to pull oneself inward to the rock so one is not out in space.  The climb itself, however, is very aesthetic.  The rock looks almost black  from what, I cannot tell  and is slippery and not nearly as heavily featured as the Sioux quartz Im used to seeing.  Once past the overhang is a series of passable hand and foot ledges which get blockier as one ascends.
content.protection: Top-rope only.  Right over the water.
content.location: South side of King Rock (to the right of the off-width/dihedral).

content.description: NE corner dihedral w/ roof at bottom
Do roof and exit to face. DON"T USE THE LEFT EDGE, but the right one you can.
content.protection: Cracks and Rock on top for top rope anchors, rappel down.

content.description: South Side of King. Slightly overhanging on small edges.
A fairly easy introduction to Palisades climbing.  Climb right-leaning dihedral to first of series of large platforms.  Blocky and easy, the crux is right off the ground.
content.protection: Can be protected with large hexes and cams.
content.location: Take the obvious right-leaning dihedral up to the top.

content.description: Very fun route, A little difficult at the bottom starting off and then nice flowing reachy moves towards the finish.
content.protection: Various spots up top to set a top rope with extended webbing or slings.
content.location: East face of King's Rock right next to the Czar.

content.description: To the left of Anthony. Do overhangs and exit straight up to the arete.
content.protection: Rock and Cracks on top for top rope, rappel down

content.description: Staying left of the corner on the right of the face. Climb the bottom two overhangs. climb face.
content.protection: Top Rope Anchors can be used rock and cracks on top, Rappel down.

content.description: A nice long sustained 5.7 in which you pull on holds resembling books not properly placed back on the shelf.  Careful, I've witnessed a few climbers yank off chunks of rock.  Make sure to warn any lost kayakers below.  Move directly up the face following the path of least resistance.
content.location: Top of the climb is a few feet upstream of the obvious tree on top of King.

content.description: Fun face climbing. Stay out of the corner/chimney.
content.location: Around the corner from King Olaf, facing upstream.

content.description: King and Queen Rock rise dramatically on the north bank of the Split Rock Creek.
